<p class="lede">
  The Pistons spent all season being the best team in the East. Sixty-something wins, the 1-seed wrapped up by April, and then they drew the Magic — the 8-seed nobody really wanted to play — and proceeded to make every Detroit fan question their cardiac fitness.
</p>

<p class="body-copy">
  Game 1 in Detroit: Orlando steals it, 112–101. The arena goes silent. Game 2: Pistons remember they're the 1-seed and lock the Magic to <em class="hl">83 points</em>. Series tied, head to Florida.
</p>

<p class="body-copy">
  Then it gets ugly. Orlando wins Game 3 at home. Orlando wins Game 4 at home — a grindy 94–88 — and suddenly the top seed in the conference is down 3–1 to an 8-seed, with the entire NBA media apparatus drafting "Greatest Choke In Recent Memory" columns in real time.
</p>

<p class="body-copy">
  Game 5 back in Detroit: <em class="hl">survival</em>. Pistons win 116–109. Game 6 in Orlando, season on the line: Detroit holds the Magic to 79 points and steals it 93–79. Defensive masterpiece, somehow, on the road, in an elimination game.
</p>

<p class="body-copy">
  Which brings us to tomorrow. Game 7. Back in Detroit. The 1-seed against the 8-seed in a winner-take-all that nobody on the projection sheet thought we'd be watching. Whoever wins this gets the second round. Whoever loses gets to think about it all summer.
</p>

